nDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92722"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of left-sided weakness and numbness. She reports being unable to move her left arm or leg. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an office administrator and mentions that her workplace has been particularly stressful lately due to impending layoffs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed but has vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals variable weakness and sensory loss that does not correspond to known anatomical distributions. When distracted, she is observed to use her left arm normally. CT and MRI scans of the brain show no acute abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther history reveals that she has recently filed a workers\u0027 compensation claim for job-related stress. When questioned about this, she becomes defensive and insists that her symptoms are real and severe.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conversion disorder","Malingering","Multiple sclerosis","Factitious disorder","Stroke"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents features typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (functional neurological disorder, FND). The key distinguishing features include symptoms that are inconsistent with known neuroanatomy, positive signs such as distractibility, and the presence of psychological stressors. Importantly, these symptoms are not consciously produced, and patients experience genuine distress. The defensive response to questioning is common and reflects the patient\u0027s legitimate suffering rather than deception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalingering\u003C/strong\u003E differs from FND in that symptoms are consciously fabricated for external gain. While the workers\u0027 compensation claim might raise this possibility, clinicians should maintain a high threshold for diagnosing malingering. Furthermore, malingering typically shows more consistent effort to display disability, whereas FND shows characteristic variability and positive signs like distractibility. Malingerers may also be more evasive during examination and less distressed by their symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E can be distinguished by several features: it typically has a gradual onset, shows demyelinating lesions on MRI, and follows clear anatomical patterns. The symptoms in MS are consistent rather than variable and are not influenced by attention or distraction. Additionally, MS typically presents with other characteristic symptoms such as visual disturbances or bladder dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactitious disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves conscious symptom production for psychological gains (such as attention or the sick role) rather than external benefits. Unlike FND, patients with factitious disorder actively create or exaggerate symptoms and may have extensive medical knowledge or history of healthcare seeking. They typically show less distress when symptoms are questioned.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStroke\u003C/strong\u003E can be readily distinguished by its consistent neurological deficits that follow vascular territories, corresponding imaging findings, and lack of variability with distraction. Acute stroke symptoms do not improve with attention or distraction, and the pattern of weakness and sensory loss follows predictable anatomical distributions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management approach differs significantly between these conditions. FND requires validation of symptoms while focusing on rehabilitation and psychological support. Malingering requires addressing underlying motivations, factitious disorder needs psychiatric intervention, and stroke/MS require specific medical treatments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Functional neurological disorder (FND) is characterized by genuine neurological symptoms that do not conform to known anatomical patterns.","Positive signs like distractibility and variability support a diagnosis of FND.","Clinicians should maintain a high threshold for diagnosing malingering and thoroughly evaluate for underlying neurological and psychiatric conditions."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association DS, American Psychiatric Association DS. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders: DSM-5. Washington, DC: American psychiatric association; 2013 May 22.","Bennett K, Diamond C, Hoeritzauer I, et al. A practical review of functional neurological disorder (FND) for the general physician. Clin Med (Lond). 2021;21(1):28-36. doi:10.7861/clinmed.2020-0987"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76089"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14552"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76089"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T22:33:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T22:33:43+10:30","number":9,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-03-18T22:33:10+10:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-7245-9.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T063807Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=a65930face33b23dc66f6c28ab9be327c40cf5a733890bbf3d895467df93a279"},"relationships":{"item